			<th scope="col">Term to use instead</th>
			<th scope="col">Reason</th>
		</tr>
	</thead>
	<tbody>
		<tr>
			<th scope="row">older person/people, elder, senior citizen</th>
			<td>Person/people of advanced age</td>
			<td>The emphasis is on the person and not their age</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<th scope="row">poor person/people, poverty-stricken person/people, ghetto, welfare king/queen</th>
			<td>person/people of low economic status</td>
			<td>the statement places emphasis on person/people, not on their economic status. In addition, some people may choose to live in low economic status because of their beliefs, which does not make them &quot;poor&quot; or &quot;poverty-stricken&quot;.</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<th scope="row">homeless person/people</th>
			<td>person/people experiencing homelessness</td>
			<td>it identifies person, not their state of home.</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<th scope="row">rich person/people</th>
			<td>person/people of high economic status</td>
			<td>it identifies person, not the fact they are rich. The term rich people/person also implies one cannot be wealthy in other ways.</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<th scope="row">overweight people/person, obese people/person, fat person/people</th>
			<td>person/people of size</td>
			<td>overweight and obese have different standards depending on culture and are medical terms that should not be used to define someone. Fat is a derogatory term.</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<th scope="row">Skinny/anorexic&nbsp;person/people, sick person/people (when referring to weight)</th>
			<td>Person/people of small size</td>
			<td>Emphasis is on person and not their size. Also, anorexia is a medical disorder and should not be used to identify someone. Also, sick defines that the person should not be that small, which is not always the case.</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<th scope="row">suffers from, stricken with, afflicted with (disabilities)</th>
			<td>lives with</td>
			<td>these terms put a negative light on disabilities and illnesses.</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<th scope="row">able-bodied person/people, whole person/people, normal person/people</th>
			<td>person/people with no disabilities</td>
			<td>Able-bodied implies those with a disability cannot perform regular tasks, which is not always true.&nbsp;The term whole and &quot;normal&quot; casts the stigma that it&#39;s not okay to be disabled.</td>
